source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-4287
Reason: The compound [1,1'-biphenyl]-4-acetamide, N-2-pyridinyl- is comprised of several structural elements influencing its melting point. The basic unit here is biphenyl, which has a melting point of around 70°C. Each phenyl ring adds to the rigidity and symmetry of the molecule, which tends to increase the melting point due to more effective π-π stacking between the molecules. The pyridinyl group (-C5H4N) is an electron-withdrawing group due to the nitrogen atom, which increases intermolecular forces via dipole interactions; it would likely add around +15°C. The acetamide group (-CONH2) is capable of hydrogen bonding which significantly increases the melting point; this could contribute approximately +30°C. However, the N-substitution on the acetamide may slightly reduce its hydrogen bonding capability, so we could estimate the increase due to the amide functionality at around +25°C. As both of these groups are ortho to each other, there will be some steric hindrance that might slightly reduce the melting point, but we will consider this effect to be relatively minor.
Prediction: The estimated melting point of [1,1'-biphenyl]-4-acetamide, N-2-pyridinyl- considering the above functional group contributions would be 70 (base biphenyl) + 15 (pyridinyl group) + 25 (acetamide group) = 110°C.
